Dimitrov's series of injury woes began 12 months ago at Wimbledon, where he slipped and damaged his knee in the first set of his fourth-round clash against Daniil Medvedev. He then retired at the US Open quarter-final with Frances Tiafoe two months later, citing physical issues.

At the Australian Open in January, Dimitrov retired in his opening match due to a groin injury and then was forced to retire from the first round last month at Roland Garros, where he suffered a leg injury that had kept him sidelined until Wimbledon.

You May Also Like: 'Pain-free' Dimitrov ready for Sinner clash following retirement nightmare

Dimitrov, the 2017 Nitto ATP Finals champion, may have entered this year's grass-court major with tempered expectations, but he found himself causing havoc on the lawns at the All England Club, where he was on the cusp of his second victory over a World No. 1 (also vs. Djokovic, Madrid 2013).



